captions.text: I know we've all lost stuff...
and you think life takes more than it gives...
Wait.  What are you doing man?
You said to give a crap!
NO NO!  That is not what I meant at all!
I mean all you do is sit in that chair ALL DAY LONG!
Is NOT having the orb going to change anything about your daily routine?
I will rule the universe, AND sit in this chair.
So bring me the orb, boy!
Why don't you get up out of that chair and make me?
I can't get out of this chair...
We have to get out of here!
I hope you have a plan!
Do not shoot those windows one at a time!
All of you fire at the same window on my command!
How would you like to get paid?
How do you think, man?  Units.
I will no longer be your slave!
Sorry!  That girl look like she was about to get in between me and becoming stupid rich...
he he he.  That'll be four billion units please.
*sings* Ooo child, it's about to get easy times.
Ooo child, things'll be bright now.
Dance off, bro!  Me and you.
Some day!  Something something in the beautiful sun!
And then, I totally destroyed EVERYTHING.
What you want to do?  Something good?
Wait.  So who's the good and who's the bad?
Hey.  I'm batman.  You wanna know my secret identity?
Do you want a fist to the face?
Me?!  If anything I'm the good, and you're the bad.
Or WE'RE the good and THEY'RE the bad.
Or You're the BAD and we're the GOOD, and Bla Bla Bla!
So, welcome back to earth I suppose.
This is awesome!  There are so many things I've missed out on!
I got this new thing called, iPod...
There's like a bazillion songs on it!
♬ butt you got a butt I got a but we all have butts.  ♬
You guys sing a lot about butts now!
So anyways.  You guys saved the galaxy!
A lot of pilots died, but hey you all held hands at the end and sort of made it all better.
You also left an infinity stone in a city that barely has any protection left.
Did you see where I got the stone the first time?
There was like nobody guarding it.
You guys and your infinity stones.
So you're like half human and half something else...
Are you not the least bit interested in knowing who your own dad is?
What?  Sorry I didn't hear you!
Did you know they made transformers movies!?
He asked who your father is!
They made Ninja Turtles into a movie too!  Several times!
I feel like he's conveniently dodging this topic.
You!  One who is part bat and part man...
Oh I'm not part bat.  I just dress like a bat...
Why do you dress like a bat?
To strike fear in the hearts of my enemies.  Duh.
Bats are not scary.  Bats are tiny mammals.
You should be called "Normal Man who dresses As Bat".
I'm not just a normal man...
This could go on for a while.
I need to see these movies right now!
and knowing is half the battle.
Who the heck did planted all these groots?!

comments.text:
HOW IN THE HELL DID AMERICA LOSE IT'S MIND AND ALLOW THIS MOVIE TO BECOME A 
SUCCESS?!! (sigh okay breathe, breathe...) Now that I've gotten that out of 
my system, I'll return to level headedness and calm reasoning. First, allow 
me to begin by saying I can see what was entertaining about this movie and 
how it can be enjoyable among some in the audience. But not to the degree 
of greatness that some people took it. I never felt like I was watching a 
superhero movie when I was watching GOTG. It didn't inspire me or move me 
or make that powerful & impacting impression on me that the dramatic hero 
epics do. I'll give you Green Lantern & Superman Returns as being bad 
movies, but I prefer the serious, dramatic, moving hero epics of the DC 
films. I'll take the Dark Knight trilogy, Man of Steel, and Watchmen films 
any day and they'll hold up well years from now whereas silly, lighthearted 
fare like Guardians won't. In my opinion, we will look back at GOTG years 
from now much the same way we look at the Adam West 1960s Batman TV show 
now. The serious, inspiring, moving hero dramas will always stand the test 
of time where the lighter, comedy-driven hero pieces will only leave us 
looking back asking to ourselves, "What were we thinking?"﻿
comments.author: Britton Thompson

comments.text:
+Britton Thompson +Wurzelknecht  I totally second everything Wurzelknecht 
said. And in addition to that, if you thought Guardians of the Galaxy was 
in no way inspiring or heroic, then you weren't paying attention. Just 
because it's funny doesn't mean it can't also be inspiring. There were 
several inspiring moments of heroic self-sacrifice. And its even more 
inspiring because these actions are coming from characters that otherwise 
seemed kind of self-interested loners. An idealistic paragon of goodness 
continuing to be a paragon of goodness is less interesting and less 
inspiring than seeing a greedy self-serving mercenary have a change of 
character, and decide to risk his life to fight for the good of the people, 
without reward of riches. It sort of says, "See, even this troublesome 
rascal can do the right thing and be a hero. Anyone can make the choice to 
step up and do the right thing. You can too." How is that not inspiring? We 
don't need superheros doing super heroic epic deeds.. All we really need is 
more people to "give a shit."
comments.author: Charles Pecaut

comments.text:
Yeah because light-hearted, entertaining movies that can also make you 
laugh will never stand the test of time. That's why nobody ever heard of 
Ghostbusters, Back to the Future, Pirates of the Caribbean, Men in Black, 
Wayne's World, or all those forgettable Indiana Jones movies. Are you just 
a pissed off DC-fanboy who has to find a reason to slander good movies 
because they're from Marvel or are you just the type who hates to laugh and 
having a good time and thinks brooding and being emo is the only thing that 
makes a real hero? If so, thanks. You are one of the people responsible for 
DC movie makers changing the character of Clark Kent in Man of Steel into a 
brooding emo guy instead of a larger than life hero who actually inspires 
hope and heroism in people like he SHOULD. Just because the Nolan-Batman 
was such a huge success, now they think they have to turn ALL their 
superheroes into Batman for them to be cool. I shudder to think what they 
will do to Wonder Woman. At least the Marvel heroes have diversity in 
character and the movies don't take themselves too seriously. Guardians was 
great for what it was. It had good action, great humor and still had enough 
time to give the characters some depth and some serious moments. Watched it 
like four times since it came out and every time I was greatly entertained. 
Watched Man of Steel once and have mixed feelings about it. Watchman gets 
tedious and longwinded with far too much slow-mo after watching it twice. 
And among the Dark Knight Trilogy only the first two, or at least the 
second one holds up every time I watch it, mostly because of the awesome 
Joker-performance. The third just raises too many questions the more you 
think about it. I like dark and serious movies as well as lighthearted and 
funny movies. Both can be great and both can suck. But implying that one is 
better because it's more "serious" and therefore will be the only thing to 
be remembered is just stupid.

comments.text:
while (true) {
  echo "I am Groot.";
  echo "I'm Batman!";
}

*Recently watched Guardians of the Galaxy again since I now know the 
significance of everything.*

Yeah, this movie exists so that Infinity Gauntlet can be established. I'm 
really not sure how Marvel / Disney can pull off something that insane and 
make anyone other than long-time Marvel fans happy. At least this movie 
introduces us to Cosmic Entities, albeit the skull of a dead one.

I mean, how is a casual audience supposed to be interested when the villain 
(Thanos) is so powerful that he takes out half the life in the universe 
just by wishing it? When The Avengers don't even begin to present a 
challenge? When the ultimate battle is between Thanos (whom we have only 
seen sitting in a chair thus far) and what are ultimately "gods" in the 
Marvel Universe? Marvel + Disney seem to have a great formula for pleasing 
fans and casual viewers alike, but I worry that they won't be able to pull 
the conclusion to all of this off.

This actually makes the third Infinity Stone / Gem we have seen. The first 
was in Loki's staff in The Avengers. Another in Thor: Dark World.

Oh, and one of the main characters in the Infinity Gauntlet was an Easter 
egg that is easy to miss in this. Adam Warlock's cocoon was one of the 
things in the Collector's gallery.

Lastly, does this mean that we're going to be getting a Nova movie or 
introduction anytime soon?﻿

comments.text:
Marvel CU movies this far from best to worst are (imo):
1. *Captain America 2* (a whole different league, excellent stand-alone spy 
movie)
2. *Guardians of the Galaxy* (great mix of story&humor, close second to CA2)
3. *Avengers* (A bit overrated but a decent movie and a lot of characters 
we love)
4. *Iron Man* (A good movie, great performance from R.D-J)
5. *Thor 2* (A good movie as well)
6. *The Incredible Hulk* (Not that great of a movie, but watchable and fun 
at times)
7. *Thor* (a bit disappointing and boring movie, but if you're a fan you 
can still enjoy it)
8. *Iron Man 3* (very disappointing movie, R.D-J presence is the only 
credit of this picture)
9. *Captain America* (not worth watching... just... don't.)
10. *Iron Man 2* (Scars for life. You know it's true. It sucked.)﻿

comments.author: Ryan O'Connell

comments.text:
I think Guardians of the Galaxy is over-rated.
Peter is the human leader, because for some reason, aliens always lack 
compassion and need a simple human to help teach them it.
Then there's Drax, the brute warrior who learns to think before he acts.
Gamora, the evil/abused space princess who learns to love.
Groot, who is a living tree and can only say one sentence, and can possibly 
revive himself after near-death experiences, which is cool. But, is that it?
And Rocket, an animal experiment who can talk. Honestly, with the hype, I 
thought he was going to be a spitfire character like Deadpool. Rocket seems 
pretty angry for most of the movie.

Maybe it's because I've never read Guardians of the Galaxy, and am not 
really a Marvel fan, but it seems really cliche. I like how it has 
anti-heroes/enemies who work toward a common good, but it's always that 
same reason; money. I think the Avengers is a better movie when it comes to 
anti-heroes/enemies becoming heroes.﻿

comments.text:
The amount of DC fans hating on this film because it isn't based on the 
second best comic company (aka DC). Marvel has been at the top for a while, 
and now that it's owned by Disney, it's sort of impossible for DC to even 
come close to matching it's abilities. We all know phase 3 will basically 
bring some of the greatest movies in years. I'm not saying DC's collection 
is horrible, but it can't compete with marvel (and I am only refering to 
movies where marvel owns the rights to the characters, spiderman for 
example is not part of this statement). The most valid argument I've seen 
so far as to why Guardians is not one of the best movies this year was that 
the plotline was too simple. Let me use Star Wars as an example. The 
plotline to all six films is good versus evil. The dark side and the light 
side, the sith and the jedi, the empire and the rebels. It's a simple 
concept, yet the Star Wars franchise has made millions, if not billions, 
because it doesn't involve a complicated storyline, and even children can 
understand the basics of the movie. ﻿

comments.text:
+Ramin Honary Yes, sort of. But then again it *is* an amusing and 
entertaining movie. It helps that the movie isn't taking itself too serious 
at all, there are tons of funny scenes in there that manage to keep you 
entertained just fine.

Just turn off your brain and imagine you're 13 again when you watch 
this.... :)

And don't expect Shakespearean levels of character development, diabolical 
twists and brilliant sub-plots ... 

I found "Hobbit 3" much worse in that regard. Not to spoil anything ... but 
e.g. I have more problems with movies that take themselves *very* serious 
but then turn out to have funny scenes in them which were *NOT* supposed to 
be 'funny' ... Hence my comment above. "Hobbit 3" is still a fantastic 
movie, sure. But when you see it you will know what I mean when I say "it's 
begging on its knees for its own 'how it should have ended' parody"....

comments.text:
I'm normally don't care for the movie plot holes, but this movie has way 
too many glaring ones that it had my mind buzzing "WTF?" all while, I was 
watching the movie. Some where covered in this video and made fun of in 
HISHE, but others like:

1) Why didn't the mother-ship have any firing power and just relies on the 
few small fighter ships to do all the fighting?
2) Why did everyone just conveniently gathers around Groot, and not try to 
gtfo (or make any plans) like any sane normal person would during the slow 
paced crashing of the mother-ship? -The scene right after the racoon 
crashes his ship on Darth Maul.
3) When Star man went out of his ship and gives Gamora his gas mask (that's 
when Gamora's shuttle was blasted apart by her sister and retrieved the 
infiinity stone) he could of easily zoom back into the safety of his pod 
and skip out on all the excessive cliche of a drama.

Sooooo much more, but meh. I'm surprised the movie did so well even with so 
many plot breaking devices.﻿

"Send them to The Kiln..."
"Hold on a second, there.  Shouldn't we maybe interrogate Gamora first?  I 
mean, do what you want with the two Han Solos and their tree-wookie over 
there, but our planet's leader just said we had a lead on Ronan's 
operations, and now you're going to stick her in general population?  
Seriously?"
An hour later...
"Gamora was really cooperative.  Turns out we all want to see Ronan and 
Thanos stopped.  And that orb thing she was after?  Our scientists looked 
at it, and there's an infinity stone inside!  Man, we would have been in 
major trouble if we'd let that get away from us.  Things worked out really 
well for everybody"
Cut to shot of Yondu sticking Quill's head on a pike and Rocket walking 
off, counting his money.

For the record, I really liked this movie, but we've seen the exact same 
formula from Marvel at least three times now.  Also, Drax is useless.﻿
